snippet.textDisplay:
I am so happy this content on YouTube exist. Even if it is only for such a short period of time. The fact that it is temporary adds certain significance to the philosophical thought experiment that is unus annus; the existential questions that arise from (some of) these videos are quite overwhelming. There is a need for these questions on media such as YouTube (who reads Sartre or Kierkegaard nowadays? I don't- just wikipediaed some names associated with 'existential dread'.) Glad to see there are other people compelled to hear them being questioned, even as we agree that there might be no answers.

Thank you, Mark & Ethan. For ...well... 'Being' I guess.

the human body and any animal for that matter, has been going through development and evolution for as long as they have existed.
its a project that has been improvising itself, building up itself, fixing itself, improving itself, for millions of years.
the body you have know is a culmination of that.
the entirety of its complexity has still not been fully understood, thats how developed we are.
not saying that we cant make robots to mimic the complexities, but that in itself requires a level of understanding of the body that we havent acquired yet.

What is the meaning to life? The answer is death.
Death gives life meaning. Without it, no one would be afraid of losing their ability to live and therefor wouldn’t be in any rush to do anything interesting.
Think about it, if you had all of eternity to live why would you do all the interesting stuff in the first 100 years? There would be no point in living if there was no death and I think that’s what Mark and Ethan are trying to teach us by deleting Unus Annus because with no end comes no reason to savour the good and bad moment when you’re alive.
Savour every single moment of Unus Annus because it will be gone soon and don’t savour it by reuploading the videos, just remember them.
